@code{taylor (@mvar{expr}, @mvar{x}, @mvar{a}, @mvar{n})} expands the expression
@mvar{expr} in a truncated Taylor or Laurent series in the variable @mvar{x}
around the point @mvar{a},
containing terms through @code{(@mvar{x} - @mvar{a})^@mvar{n}}.

If @mvar{expr} is of the form @code{@mvar{f}(@mvar{x})/@mvar{g}(@mvar{x})} and
@code{@mvar{g}(@mvar{x})} has no terms up to degree @mvar{n} then @code{taylor}
attempts to expand @code{@mvar{g}(@mvar{x})} up to degree @code{2 @mvar{n}}.
If there are still no nonzero terms, @code{taylor} doubles the degree of the
expansion of @code{@mvar{g}(@mvar{x})} so long as the degree of the expansion is
less than or equal to @code{@mvar{n} 2^taylordepth}.

@code{taylor (@mvar{expr}, [@mvar{x_1}, @mvar{x_2}, ...], @mvar{a}, @mvar{n})}
returns a truncated power series 
of degree @mvar{n} in all variables @mvar{x_1}, @mvar{x_2}, @dots{}
about the point @code{(@mvar{a}, @mvar{a}, ...)}.

@code{taylor (@mvar{expr}, [@mvar{x_1}, @mvar{a_1}, @mvar{n_1}], [@mvar{x_2},
@mvar{a_2}, @mvar{n_2}], ...)} returns a truncated power series in the variables
@mvar{x_1}, @mvar{x_2}, @dots{} about the point
@code{(@mvar{a_1}, @mvar{a_2}, ...)}, truncated at @mvar{n_1}, @mvar{n_2}, @dots{}

@code{taylor (@mvar{expr}, [@mvar{x_1}, @mvar{x_2}, ...], [@mvar{a_1},
@mvar{a_2}, ...], [@mvar{n_1}, @mvar{n_2}, ...])} returns a truncated power series
in the variables @mvar{x_1}, @mvar{x_2}, @dots{} about the point
@code{(@mvar{a_1}, @mvar{a_2}, ...)}, truncated at @mvar{n_1}, @mvar{n_2}, @dots{}

@code{taylor (@mvar{expr}, [@mvar{x}, @mvar{a}, @mvar{n}, 'asymp])} returns an
expansion of @mvar{expr} in negative powers of @code{@mvar{x} - @mvar{a}}.
The highest order term is @code{(@mvar{x} - @mvar{a})^@mvar{-n}}.

When @code{maxtayorder} is @code{true}, then during algebraic
manipulation of (truncated) Taylor series, @code{taylor} tries to retain
as many terms as are known to be correct.

When @code{psexpand} is @code{true},
an extended rational function expression is displayed fully expanded.
The switch @code{ratexpand} has the same effect.
When @code{psexpand} is @code{false},
a multivariate expression is displayed just as in the rational function package.
When @code{psexpand} is  @code{multi},
