@anchor{poissubst}
@deffn {Function} poissubst (@mvar{a}, @mvar{b}, @mvar{c})

Substitutes @mvar{a} for @mvar{b} in @mvar{c}.  @mvar{c} is a Poisson series.

(1) Where @mvar{B} is a variable @mvar{u}, @mvar{v}, @mvar{w}, @mvar{x}, @mvar{y},
or @mvar{z}, then @mvar{a} must be an expression linear in those variables (e.g.,
@code{6*u + 4*v}).

(2) Where @mvar{b} is other than those variables, then @mvar{a} must also be
free of those variables, and furthermore, free of sines or cosines.

@code{poissubst (@mvar{a}, @mvar{b}, @mvar{c}, @mvar{d}, @mvar{n})} is a special type
of substitution which operates on @mvar{a} and @mvar{b} as in type (1) above, but
where @mvar{d} is a Poisson series, expands @code{cos(@mvar{d})} and
@code{sin(@mvar{d})} to order @mvar{n} so as to provide the result of substituting
@code{@mvar{a} + @mvar{d}} for @mvar{b} in @mvar{c}.  The idea is that @mvar{d} is an
expansion in terms of a small parameter.  For example,
@code{poissubst (u, v, cos(v), %e, 3)} yields
@code{cos(u)*(1 - %e^2/2) - sin(u)*(%e - %e^3/6)}.

@opencatbox
@category{Poisson series}
@closecatbox
@end deffn

